    {
      "id": "claim_001",
      "context": "explicit",
      "subject": "explicit",
      "qualifier": "consistent_with",
      "relation": "describes",
      "object": "This repository contains code and data described in detail in a paper by Engler et al., 2024.",
      "@type": "asb:Claim",
      "source_task_kind_status": "ambiguous_multi_kind"
    },
    {
      "@type": "sepio:0000002",
      "id": "claim_001_evidence",
      "evidence_for": "claim_001",
      "text_selector": {
        "@type": "oa:TextQuoteSelector",
        "exact": null
      },
      "workflow_coupling": "loose"
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_001/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "we evaluated state-of-the-art Graph Neural Networks (GNNs), trained to predict CCS values using the largest publicly available dataset to date. Although our results confirm the high accuracy of these models within chemical spaces similar to their training environments, their performance significantly declines when applied to structurally novel regions.",
      "asbval:note": "The research question directly aligns with the paper's core investigation of GNN generalizability for CCS prediction.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Can graph neural network models trained for collision cross section prediction generalize effectively to held-out test data?",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:15:55.612364+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_001/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The SigmaCCS architecture consists of a GNN with three ECC layers [19] trained on three matrices representing the molecular graph... In our implementation of Mol2CCS, the GNN module is identical to SigmaCCS's implementation",
      "asbval:note": "Paper uses GNNs (specifically SigmaCCS and GraphCCS with Edge-Conditioned Convolutions and Graph Convolutional Networks), but does not explicitly name PyTorch Geometric. The paper implements GNNs but the specific framework is not stated in passages.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Graph Neural Network (GNN) framework (PyTorch Geometric or equivalent)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:15:55.612364+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_001/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "No mention of 'enveda/ccs-prediction' repository or any GitHub repository in the provided passages. The paper references SigmaCCS [6] and GraphCCS [22] as existing models that were retrained, but does not cite a specific 'enveda' repository.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "enveda/ccs-prediction repository (model code and pre-trained weights)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:15:55.612364+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_001/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We evaluated the performance of the models on a test set using several metrics. We employed correlation metrics such as coefficient of determination (R2), Pearson and Spearman correlation. Additionally, we used mean absolute error (MAE), mean squared error (MSE), root mean squared error (RMSE), relative standard deviation (RSD), and the relative error in percentage between the predicted CCS values and the experimental ones",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly reports RMSE, MAE, and R\u00b2 metrics on held-out test sets across multiple evaluation scenarios.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Generalizability metrics table (RMSE, MAE, R\u00b2) computed on held-out test data",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:15:55.612364+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_001/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Figure 2 shows the predicted CCS and the actual experimental values as well as the corresponding metrics for the three benchmarked models, when they are evaluated on a test set of the same database where they were trained.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper reports predicted vs. experimental CCS values in scatterplots and figures for test sets, though molecular identifiers are not explicitly listed in passages shown.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Model predictions on test set (molecular identifiers and predicted vs. ground-truth CCS values)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:15:55.612364+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_001/scope_drift",
      "@type": "asbval:ScopeDriftAssertion",
      "asbval:drift_notes": [
        "The candidate card frames the task as 'reproducing' a generalizability evaluation, but the paper itself IS the generalizability evaluation study. The card does not clarify whether it seeks to reproduce the authors' own work or apply their methodology to new data.",
        "The card does not mention the key contribution of the paper: the introduction of Mol2CCS (an extension of SigmaCCS with additional features) or the use of confidence models to improve predictions. These are central to the paper's novelty.",
        "The card omits the two main datasets used (CCSBase and METLIN-CCS) and the three evaluation scenarios (same database, cross-database, combined dataset), which are essential to understanding the scope of the generalizability study."
      ],
      "asbval:n_drift_notes": 3,
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:15:55.612364+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_002/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "The paper does not conduct feature importance analysis, ablation studies, or saliency analysis on GNN predictions. The paper benchmarks three models (GraphCCS, SigmaCCS, Mol2CCS) and evaluates their generalizability across datasets, but does not investigate which structural features drive predictions. The paper does describe features used in Mol2CCS (node/edge attributes, Morgan fingerprints, molecular weight, structural classes, molecule types, instrument type) but does not analyze their relative importance or contribution to predictions.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_002",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Which molecular structural features are most important for driving graph neural network predictions of collision cross section?",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:16:08.440023+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_002/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "No feature importance ranking, ablation study results, or saliency scores are reported in the paper. The paper lists features used in Mol2CCS (Supplementary Table 1) but does not rank them by importance or provide ablation analysis.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_002",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Ranked feature-importance table (CSV or TSV) listing node/edge features sorted by ablation or saliency score",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:16:08.440023+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_002/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "No feature importance visualizations (bar plots, heatmaps, or similar) are presented. The paper includes scatterplots of predictions vs. experimental values and performance metrics, but no feature contribution analysis.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_002",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Feature-importance visualization (bar plot or heatmap) showing relative contribution of top structural features to CCS prediction",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:16:08.440023+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_002/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "we expanded upon the codebase for its implementation... The SigmaCCS architecture consists of a GNN with three ECC layers [19] trained on three matrices representing the molecular graph",
      "asbval:note": "The paper does not explicitly name PyTorch or TensorFlow as the deep learning framework used. The paper states Mol2CCS is 'an extension of SigmaCCS' and describes the architecture but does not specify the underlying framework. SigmaCCS (the base model) may use either framework, but this is not stated in the provided passages. The paper does mention 'scikit-learn' for the confidence model (passage 6) but not the main DL framework.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_002",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "PyTorch or TensorFlow",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:16:08.440023+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_002/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "we first read the SMILES representation of each molecule using RDKit (v2023.09.5) [8] and subsequently used the ETKDG and MMFF94 conformer generators to obtain the 3D conformers for each molecule",
      "asbval:note": "RDKit is explicitly used for SMILES parsing and conformer generation. Also mentioned: 'Morgan fingerprints (iii), generated using RDKit with 256 bits and radius of 2' (passage 4).",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_002",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "RDKit",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:16:08.440023+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_002/scope_drift",
      "@type": "asbval:ScopeDriftAssertion",
      "asbval:drift_notes": [
        "The candidate task card proposes a feature importance / interpretability analysis task that is fundamentally different from the paper's actual scope. The paper is a benchmarking and generalizability study of CCS prediction models, not an interpretability or feature attribution study.",
        "The paper describes features used in Mol2CCS but does not perform ablation studies, saliency analysis, or feature importance ranking\u2014all of which would be required to answer the proposed research question.",
        "The paper's focus is on model performance across different chemical spaces and the use of confidence models to filter predictions, not on understanding which structural features drive predictions."
      ],
      "asbval:n_drift_notes": 3,
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_002",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:16:08.440023+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_003/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "In this analysis, the SMILES strings available in both datasets are the base representation leveraged to generate molecular fingerprints and graph representations... To construct them, we first read the SMILES representation of each molecule using RDKit (v2023.09.5) [8] and subsequently used the ETKDG and MMFF94 conformer generators to obtain the 3D conformers for each molecule. Lastly, from these conformers, we obtained the atoms, bonds and their attributes... The entire molecular graph is represented by three different matrices: i) node attribute matrix, ii) edge attribute matrix, and iii) adjacency matrix.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper explicitly describes SMILES preprocessing and conversion to graph representations with node/edge/adjacency matrices for GNN input.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_003",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "How are SMILES strings from the CCS dataset preprocessed and converted into graph tensor representations suitable for GNN input?",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:16:22.019646+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_003/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The entire molecular graph is represented by three different matrices: i) node attribute matrix, ii) edge attribute matrix, and iii) adjacency matrix. These three matrices respectively store characteristic attributes of the atoms, bonds, and the connections of the molecular graph.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes the three matrices (node attributes, edge attributes, adjacency) that constitute the graph representation, but does not explicitly mention serialization format (PyTorch tensors or pickle files). The paper uses RDKit and mentions training with these representations but does not specify the exact serialization format of the output dataset.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_003",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Serialized graph dataset file containing atom/bond feature tensors and molecular graphs in PyTorch or pickle format",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:16:22.019646+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_003/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "No mention of 'manual expert review' appears in the paper. The paper uses automated tools: RDKit (v2023.09.5) for SMILES reading and conformer generation (ETKDG, MMFF94), and scikit-learn for confidence models. No manual expert review step is described in the graph construction pipeline.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_003",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "manual expert review",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:16:22.019646+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_003/scope_drift",
      "@type": "asbval:ScopeDriftAssertion",
      "asbval:drift_notes": [
        "The candidate card focuses narrowly on the graph construction step as a standalone task, but the paper presents this as part of a broader benchmarking study of GNN generalizability for CCS prediction. The card does not reflect the paper's main research question about model generalizability across chemical spaces.",
        "The card frames the task as 'reconstruction' of a graph construction step, implying reverse-engineering or documentation of an existing process, but the paper describes the methods used in their own pipeline, not a reconstruction task."
      ],
      "asbval:n_drift_notes": 2,
