      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/atom-feature-extraction-chemistry/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We first dropped rows with missing SMILES and SMILES with a '.', implying multiple disconnected parts.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper validates SMILES quality (drops malformed ones) but does not explicitly discuss canonicalization as a prerequisite step. The paper uses SMILES 'available in both datasets' without explicitly stating they are canonicalized before feature extraction.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "atom-feature-extraction-chemistry",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When NOT to use: SMILES strings are non-canonical or malformed; canonicalization must precede feature extraction.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:18:33.536920+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/atom-feature-extraction-chemistry/008",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "we first read the SMILES representation of each molecule using RDKit (v2023.09.5) [8] and subsequently used the ETKDG and MMFF94 conformer generators to obtain the 3D conformers for each molecule. Lastly, from these conformers, we obtained the atoms, bonds and their attributes.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper does generate 3D conformers (ETKDG, MMFF94) as a separate step before extracting atom/bond attributes, supporting the claim that 3D coordinates are a separate concern. However, the card's claim that this skill 'extracts connectivity and atom/bond properties only' is not fully accurate\u2014the paper extracts attributes derived from 3D conformers, not purely from SMILES connectivity.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "atom-feature-extraction-chemistry",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When NOT to use: You need 3D spatial coordinates (e.g., for distance-based features); this skill extracts connectivity and atom/bond properties only\u2014use a separate 3D coordinate generation step",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:18:33.536920+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/collision-cross-section-prediction-evaluation/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "In this work we benchmark the state-of-the-art models on the new METLIN-CCS database and assess their generalizability... We evaluated the performance of the models on a test set using several metrics. We employed correlation metrics such as coefficient of determination (R2), Pearson and Spearman correlation. Additionally, we used mean absolute error (MAE), mean squared error (MSE), root mean squared error (RMSE), relative standard deviation (RSD), and the relative error in percentage between the predicted CCS values and the experimental ones",
      "asbval:note": "Core research question is directly supported by paper's methodology and metrics.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "collision-cross-section-prediction-evaluation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Evaluate the generalizability of graph neural network models trained for collision cross section (CCS) prediction by executing inference on held-out test sets and computing standardized accuracy metrics (RMSE, MAE, R\u00b2)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:18:50.232063+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/collision-cross-section-prediction-evaluation/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "For the second method we trained the model on the training set for one database and used the other database as a test set. The rationale behind this setting was to evaluate the generalizability of both datasets and models... When training on the CCSBase train set and evaluating on the entire METLIN-CCS... the performance significantly drops across all models; thus, indicating the lack of generality of the models when predicting within an unseen chemical space.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly evaluates cross-database generalizability.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "collision-cross-section-prediction-evaluation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This skill validates whether CCS predictors trained on one molecular database generalize effectively to unseen compounds and alternative reference datasets",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
