    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/inference-performance-benchmarking/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We evaluated the performance of the two most accurate ML models trained to predict CCS values: GraphCCS [22], and SigmaCCS [6]. We retrained these models using the reported hyperparameters on the datasets used in this work... We benchmarked all the models using three different settings... We evaluated the performance of the models on a test set using several metrics... Additionally, we used mean absolute error (MAE), mean squared error (MSE), root mean squared error (RMSE), relative standard deviation (RSD), and the relative error in percentage between the predicted CCS values and the experimental ones (% CCS error).",
      "asbval:note": "Paper evaluates GNN architectures (GraphCCS, SigmaCCS, Mol2CCS) and reports RMSE and MAE metrics on test sets. However, the paper does NOT explicitly measure or report inference speed or training time comparisons. The card claims 'measuring inference speed, training time' but these metrics are not presented in the passages. The paper focuses on predictive accuracy metrics only.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "inference-performance-benchmarking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Evaluate and compare the computational efficiency and predictive accuracy of alternative GNN architectures for collision cross section prediction by measuring inference speed, training time, and regression metrics (RMSE, MAE) on held-out test sets.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:20:28.552588+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/inference-performance-benchmarking/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "In this work we benchmark the state-of-the-art models on the new METLIN-CCS database and assess their generalizability. We also demonstrate increased generalizability using an extension of SigmaCCS, which we call Mol2CCS, that incorporates additional information such as instrument type.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly benchmarks models and assesses generalizability across different chemical spaces and datasets.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "inference-performance-benchmarking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This skill enables quantitative assessment of whether architectural changes improve model performance without sacrificing generalizability.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:20:28.552588+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/inference-performance-benchmarking/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We retrained these models using the reported hyperparameters on the datasets used in this work... We trained the model up to 400 epochs applying early stopping using a patience of 10 epochs. Furthermore, we used a dropout of 0.1 for the novel module, a batch size of 32, an Adam optimizer with a learning rate of 0.0001...",
      "asbval:note": "Paper retrains GraphCCS and SigmaCCS with reported hyperparameters and describes Mol2CCS hyperparameters in detail. However, the paper does not explicitly state that all three models were trained with identical hyperparameters, loss functions, and optimization settings. Mol2CCS is an extension of SigmaCCS with different architecture, so training conditions may differ.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "inference-performance-benchmarking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "You have trained two or more graph neural network models on the same CCS dataset split (using identical hyperparameters, loss functions, and optimization settings)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:20:28.552588+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/inference-performance-benchmarking/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "For the second method we trained the model on the training set for one database and used the other database as a test set. The rationale behind this setting was to evaluate the generalizability of both datasets and models... When training on the CCSBase train set and evaluating on the entire METLIN-CCS... When we trained on METLIN-CCS, which has more dimers, and evaluated on CCSBase...",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly addresses cross-dataset evaluation as a separate workflow to assess generalization under domain shift.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "inference-performance-benchmarking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "test set has significant domain shift from training data (e.g., testing on CCSBase when trained on METLIN only)\u2014use separate generalization evaluation workflows",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
