    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-ccs-prediction-model-training/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "METLIN-CCS (downloaded on 14/04/2024) is currently the largest CCS database with over 65,000 CCS values from 27,633 distinct small synthetic molecules. METLIN-CCS contains CCS values exclusively measured in timsTOF Pro for trapped ion mobility spectrometry (TIMS) and CCS values for individual adduct forms were experimentally acquired in triplicates.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper uses METLIN-CCS and CCSBase, both containing SMILES, adduct information, and experimental CCS values. 3D coordinates are generated from SMILES using RDKit conformer generators.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-ccs-prediction-model-training",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "curated dataset of small molecules with SMILES, optional 3D coordinates, adduct information, and experimentally measured CCS values",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:21:32.877981+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-ccs-prediction-model-training/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The first model, SigmaCCS [6], employs Edge-Conditioned Convolutions (ECCs) [19] to embed the original molecular structure along with the adduct type. The second GNN, GraphCCS [22], simulates the structure of the resulting adduct and uses it as input for a Graph Convolutional Network (GCN).",
      "asbval:note": "Paper compares SigmaCCS (ECC-based) and GraphCCS (GCN-based), but does not explicitly evaluate GAT or MPNN architectures. The paper does compare message-passing designs but not the full set claimed in the card.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-ccs-prediction-model-training",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "establish a baseline GNN architecture or compare alternative message-passing designs (GAT, MPNN, GraphConv) under controlled hyperparameter conditions",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:21:32.877981+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-ccs-prediction-model-training/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We trained and tested each model on train and test splits using the following strategy. First, we divided the entire dataset (CCSBase and METLIN-CCS data combined) into five distinct groups: lipids, dimers carbohydrates, peptides, and everything else. This categorization ensured that each of these categories was represented in the train and test sets. We performed an 80/20 train test split on each of these groups stratified on the Murcko scaffold.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper uses standardized 80/20 train/test splits with scaffold stratification. Hyperparameters are controlled: 'We chose these parameters based on a grid search experiment conducted on a subset of the dataset.'",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-ccs-prediction-model-training",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "held-out test molecules with controlled hyperparameter conditions",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:21:32.877981+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-dataset-partitioning-and-preprocessing/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We first dropped rows with missing SMILES and SMILES with a \".\", implying multiple disconnected parts. In CCSBase multiple instances of duplicate SMILES-adduct pairs were present. To address this issue, we calculated the standard deviation of the CCS values associated with each SMILES-adduct pair. We removed any pairs with a mean absolute deviation greater than five... We then assigned the mean CCS value for each pair to the remaining duplicates... We trained and tested each model on train and test splits using the following strategy. First, we divided the entire dataset (CCSBase and METLIN-CCS data combined) into five distinct groups: lipids, dimers carbohydrates, peptides, and everything else... We performed an 80/20 train test split on each of these groups stratified on the Murcko scaffold.",
      "asbval:note": "Core task of preprocessing and partitioning is explicitly described in the Methods section.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00899-w",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-dataset-partitioning-and-preprocessing",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Prepare molecular structure and collision cross section data for training and evaluating graph neural network models by applying standardized preprocessing and partitioning into train/validation/test splits.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:21:50.721452+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
