      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "For this work, we leveraged two of the largest public resources for CCS values: CCSBase [17] and METLIN-CCS [1]... In this analysis, the SMILES strings available in both datasets are the base representation leveraged to generate molecular fingerprints and graph representations.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper does use SMILES from CCSBase and METLIN-CCS, but does not address the problem of non-canonical notations or canonicalization as a preprocessing step. The scope description assumes canonicalization is performed, but the paper's actual preprocessing only removes invalid SMILES.",
